flixel.FlxBasic.name: FlxBasic
flixel.FlxBasic.description:
This is a useful "generic" Flixel object. Both FlxObject and
FlxGroup extend this class. Has no size, position or graphical data.

flixel.FlxCamera.name: FlxCamera
flixel.FlxCamera.description:
The camera class is used to display the game's visuals.
By default one camera is created automatically, that is the same size as window.
You can add more cameras or even replace the main camera using utilities in FlxG.cameras.

flixel.FlxG.name: FlxG
flixel.FlxG.description: Global helper class for audio, input, the camera system, the debugger and other global properties.

flixel.FlxGame.name: FlxGame
flixel.FlxGame.description:
FlxGame is the heart of all Flixel games, and contains a bunch of basic game loops and things.
It is a long and sloppy file that you shouldn't have to worry about too much!
It is basically only used to create your game object in the first place,
after that FlxG and FlxState have all the useful stuff you actually need.

flixel.FlxObject.name: FlxObject
flixel.FlxObject.description:
This is the base class for most of the display objects (FlxSprite, FlxText, etc).
It includes some basic attributes about game objects, basic state information,
sizes, scrolling, and basic physics and motion.

flixel.FlxSprite.name: FlxSprite
flixel.FlxSprite.description:
The main "game object" class, the sprite is a FlxObject
with a bunch of graphics options and abilities, like animation and stamping.

flixel.FlxState.name: FlxState
flixel.FlxState.description:
This is the basic game "state" object - e.g. in a simple game you might have a menu state and a play state.
It is for all intents and purpose a fancy FlxGroup. And really, it's not even that fancy.

flixel.FlxStrip.name: FlxStrip
flixel.FlxStrip.description:
A very basic rendering component which uses drawTriangles().
You have access to vertices, indices and uvtData vectors which are used as data storages for rendering.
The whole FlxGraphic object is used as a texture for this sprite.
Use these links for more info about drawTriangles():

flixel.FlxSubState.name: FlxSubState
flixel.FlxSubState.description:
A FlxSubState can be opened inside of a FlxState.
By default, it also stops the parent state from updating,
making it convenient for pause screens or menus.

flixel.FlxType.name: FlxType
flixel.FlxType.description: Types of flixel objects - mainly for collisions.

spinehaxe.Skin.name: Skin
spinehaxe.Skin.description: Stores attachments by slot index and attachment name.

flixel.animation.FlxAnimation.name: FlxAnimation
flixel.animation.FlxAnimation.description: Just a helper structure for the FlxSprite animation system.

flixel.effects.FlxFlicker.name: FlxFlicker
flixel.effects.FlxFlicker.description:
The retro flickering effect with callbacks.
You can use this as a mixin in any FlxObject subclass or by calling the static functions.

flixel.graphics.FlxGraphic.name: FlxGraphic
flixel.graphics.FlxGraphic.description:
BitmapData wrapper which is used for rendering.
It stores info about all frames, generated for specific BitmapData object.

flixel.group.FlxTypedGroup.name: FlxTypedGroup
flixel.group.FlxTypedGroup.description:
This is an organizational class that can update and render a bunch of FlxBasics.
NOTE: Although FlxGroup extends FlxBasic, it will not automatically
add itself to the global collisions quad tree, it will only add its members.

flixel.group.FlxTypedGroupIterator.name: FlxTypedGroupIterator
flixel.group.FlxTypedGroupIterator.description:
Iterator implementation for groups
Support a filter method (used for iteratorAlive, iteratorDead and iteratorExists)

flixel.group.FlxTypedSpriteGroup.name: FlxTypedSpriteGroup
flixel.group.FlxTypedSpriteGroup.description:
FlxSpriteGroup is a special FlxSprite that can be treated like
a single sprite even if it's made up of several member sprites.
It shares the FlxTypedGroup API, but it doesn't inherit from it.

flixel.input.FlxKeyManager.name: FlxKeyManager
flixel.input.FlxKeyManager.description:
Keeps track of what keys are pressed and how with handy Bools or strings.
Automatically instatiated by flixel as a FlxKeyboard and accessed via FlxG.keys
or FlxAndroidKeys with FlxG.android.
Example: FlxG.keys.justPressed.A

flixel.math.FlxAngle.name: FlxAngle
flixel.math.FlxAngle.description: A set of functions related to angle calculations.

flixel.math.FlxCallbackPoint.name: FlxCallbackPoint
flixel.math.FlxCallbackPoint.description:
A FlxPoint that calls a function when set_x(), set_y() or set() is called. Used in FlxSpriteGroup.
IMPORTANT: Calling set(x, y); is MUCH FASTER than setting x and y separately. Needs to be destroyed unlike simple FlxPoints!

flixel.math.FlxMath.name: FlxMath
flixel.math.FlxMath.description: A class containing a set of math-related functions.

flixel.math.FlxMatrix.name: FlxMatrix
flixel.math.FlxMatrix.description:
Helper class for making fast matrix calculations for rendering.
It mostly copies Matrix class, but with some additions for
faster rotation by 90 degrees.

flixel.math.FlxRandom.name: FlxRandom
flixel.math.FlxRandom.description: A class containing a set of functions for random generation.

flixel.system.FlxLinkedList.name: FlxLinkedList
flixel.system.FlxLinkedList.description:
A miniature linked list class.
Useful for optimizing time-critical or highly repetitive tasks!
See FlxQuadTree for how to use it, IF YOU DARE.

flixel.system.FlxPreloader.name: FlxPreloader

flixel.system.FlxQuadTree.name: FlxQuadTree
flixel.system.FlxQuadTree.description:
A fairly generic quad tree structure for rapid overlap checks.
FlxQuadTree is also configured for single or dual list operation.
You can add items either to its A list or its B list.
When you do an overlap check, you can compare the A list to itself,
or the A list against the B list.  Handy for different things!

flixel.system.FlxSound.name: FlxSound
flixel.system.FlxSound.description: This is the universal flixel sound object, used for streaming, music, and sound effects.

flixel.system.FlxSoundGroup.name: FlxSoundGroup
flixel.system.FlxSoundGroup.description: A way of grouping sounds for things such as collective volume control

flixel.text.FlxBitmapText.name: FlxBitmapText
flixel.text.FlxBitmapText.description:
Extends FlxSprite to support rendering text.
Can tint, fade, rotate and scale just like a sprite.
Doesn't really animate though, as far as I know.

flixel.text.FlxText.name: FlxText
flixel.text.FlxText.description:
Extends FlxSprite to support rendering text. Can tint, fade, rotate and scale just like a sprite. Doesn't really animate
though. Also does nice pixel-perfect centering on pixel fonts as long as they are only one-liners.

flixel.tile.FlxTile.name: FlxTile
flixel.tile.FlxTile.description:
A simple helper object for FlxTilemap that helps expand collision opportunities and control.
You can use FlxTilemap.setTileProperties() to alter the collision properties and
callback functions and filters for this object to do things like one-way tiles or whatever.

flixel.tile.FlxTileblock.name: FlxTileblock
flixel.tile.FlxTileblock.description:
This is a basic "environment object" class, used to create simple walls and floors.
It can be filled with a random selection of tiles to quickly add detail.

flixel.tile.FlxTilemap.name: FlxTilemap
flixel.tile.FlxTilemap.description:
This is a traditional tilemap display and collision class. It takes a string of comma-separated numbers and then associates
those values with tiles from the sheet you pass in. It also includes some handy static parsers that can convert
arrays or images into strings that can be loaded.

flixel.tile.FlxTilemapBuffer.name: FlxTilemapBuffer
flixel.tile.FlxTilemapBuffer.description:
A helper object to keep tilemap drawing performance decent across the new multi-camera system.
Pretty much don't even have to think about this class unless you are doing some crazy hacking.

flixel.tweens.FlxEase.name: FlxEase
flixel.tweens.FlxEase.description: Static class with useful easer functions that can be used by tweens.

flixel.tweens.FlxTweenManager.name: FlxTweenManager
flixel.tweens.FlxTweenManager.description:
A simple manager for tracking and updating game tween objects.
Normally accessed via the static FlxTween.globalManager rather than being created separately.

flixel.ui.FlxAnalog.name: FlxAnalog
flixel.ui.FlxAnalog.description: A virtual thumbstick - useful for input on mobile devices.

flixel.ui.FlxBar.name: FlxBar
flixel.ui.FlxBar.description:
FlxBar is a quick and easy way to create a graphical bar which can
be used as part of your UI/HUD, or positioned next to a sprite.
It could represent a loader, progress or health bar.

flixel.ui.FlxBitmapTextButton.name: FlxBitmapTextButton
flixel.ui.FlxBitmapTextButton.description: A button with FlxBitmapText field as a label.

flixel.ui.FlxButton.name: FlxButton
flixel.ui.FlxButton.description: A simple button class that calls a function when clicked by the mouse.

flixel.ui.FlxSpriteButton.name: FlxSpriteButton
flixel.ui.FlxSpriteButton.description: A simple button class that calls a function when clicked by the mouse.

flixel.ui.FlxTypedButton.name: FlxTypedButton
flixel.ui.FlxTypedButton.description: A simple button class that calls a function when clicked by the mouse.

flixel.ui.FlxVirtualPad.name: FlxVirtualPad
flixel.ui.FlxVirtualPad.description:
A gamepad which contains 4 directional buttons and 4 action buttons.
It's easy to set the callbacks and to customize the layout.

flixel.util.FlxArrayUtil.name: FlxArrayUtil
flixel.util.FlxArrayUtil.description: A set of functions for array manipulation.

flixel.util.FlxBitmapDataUtil.name: FlxBitmapDataUtil
flixel.util.FlxBitmapDataUtil.description:
Just a collection of BitmapData utility methods.
Just for cross-platform stuff, since not all methods are implemented across all targets.

flixel.util.FlxGradient.name: FlxGradient
flixel.util.FlxGradient.description: Adds a set of color gradient creation / rendering functions

flixel.util.FlxPath.name: FlxPath
flixel.util.FlxPath.description:
This is a simple path data container. Basically a list of points that
a FlxObject can follow.  Also has code for drawing debug visuals.
FlxTilemap.findPath() returns a path usable by FlxPath, but you can
also just make your own, using the add() functions below
or by creating your own array of points.

flixel.util.FlxPool.name: FlxPool
flixel.util.FlxPool.description:
A generic container that facilitates pooling and recycling of objects.
WARNING: Pooled objects must have parameter-less constructors: function new()

flixel.util.FlxSave.name: FlxSave
flixel.util.FlxSave.description:
A class to help automate and simplify save game functionality.
Basically a wrapper for the Flash SharedObject thing, but
handles some annoying storage request stuff too.

flixel.util.FlxSort.name: FlxSort
flixel.util.FlxSort.description: Helper class for sort() in FlxTypedGroup, but could theoretically be used on regular arrays as well.

flixel.util.FlxSpriteUtil.name: FlxSpriteUtil
flixel.util.FlxSpriteUtil.description:
Some handy functions for FlxSprite (FlxObject) manipulation, mostly drawing-related.
Note that stage quality impacts the results of the draw() functions -
use FlxG.stage.quality = flash.display.StageQuality.BEST; for best results.

flixel.util.FlxStringUtil.name: FlxStringUtil
flixel.util.FlxStringUtil.description:
A class primarily containing functions related
to formatting different data types to strings.

flixel.util.FlxTimer.name: FlxTimer
flixel.util.FlxTimer.description:
A simple timer class, leveraging the new plugins system.
Can be used with callbacks or by polling the finished flag.
Not intended to be added to a game state or group; the timer manager
is responsible for actually calling update(), not the user.

flixel.util.FlxTimerManager.name: FlxTimerManager
flixel.util.FlxTimerManager.description:
A simple manager for tracking and updating game timer objects.
Normally accessed via the static FlxTimer.manager rather than being created separately.

flixel.util.FlxColor.name: FlxColor
flixel.util.FlxColor.description: Class representing a color, based on Int. Provides a variety of methods for creating and converting colors.

flixel.util.FlxDirection.name: FlxDirection
flixel.util.FlxDirection.description: Simple enum for orthogonal directions. Can be combined into FlxDirectionFlags.

flixel.util.FlxDirectionFlags.name: FlxDirectionFlags
flixel.util.FlxDirectionFlags.description:
Uses bit flags to create a list of orthogonal directions. useful for
many FlxObject features like allowCollisions and touching.

lime.app.Application.name: Application
lime.app.Application.description:
The Application class forms the foundation for most Lime projects.
It is common to extend this class in a main class. It is then possible
to override "on" functions in the class in order to handle standard events
that are relevant.

lime.app.Event.name: Event
lime.app.Event.description:
Event is a strictly-typed signals and slots implementation, used for
core event dispatching.

lime.app.Future.name: Future
lime.app.Future.description:
Future is an implementation of Futures and Promises, with the exception that
in addition to "success" and "failure" states (represented as "complete" and "error"),
Lime Future introduces "progress" feedback as well to increase the value of
Future values.

lime.app.Module.name: Module
lime.app.Module.description:
Module instances can be added to a running Application,
simplifying support for adding new components, such as a renderer,
input handler or higher-level framework.

lime.app.Promise.name: Promise
lime.app.Promise.description:
Promise is an implementation of Futures and Promises, with the exception that
in addition to "success" and "failure" states (represented as "complete" and "error"),
Lime Future introduces "progress" feedback as well to increase the value of
Future values.

lime.graphics.Image.name: Image
lime.graphics.Image.description: Image is a convenience class for working with bitmap images in Lime.

lime.graphics.ImageBuffer.name: ImageBuffer
lime.graphics.ImageBuffer.description: ImageBuffer is a simple object for storing image data.

lime.graphics.RenderContext.name: RenderContext
lime.graphics.RenderContext.description: The RenderContext provides access to rendering for a Lime Window.

lime.graphics.CairoRenderContext.name: CairoRenderContext
lime.graphics.CairoRenderContext.description:
The CairoRenderContext represents the primary lime.graphics.Cairo instance when Cairo
is the render context type of the Window.

lime.graphics.OpenGLES2RenderContext.name: OpenGLES2RenderContext
lime.graphics.OpenGLES2RenderContext.description:
The OpenGLES2RenderContext allows access to OpenGL ES 2.0 features when OpenGL or
OpenGL ES is the render context type of the Window.

lime.graphics.PixelFormat.name: PixelFormat
lime.graphics.PixelFormat.description: An enum containing different pixel encoding formats for image data

lime.graphics.RenderContextType.name: RenderContextType
lime.graphics.RenderContextType.description: An enum for possible render context types

lime.graphics.WebGL2RenderContext.name: WebGL2RenderContext
lime.graphics.WebGL2RenderContext.description:
The WebGL2RenderContext allows access to WebGL 2 features when OpenGL, OpenGL ES
or WebGL is the render context type of the Window, and the current context supports
WebGL 2 features.

lime.graphics.WebGLRenderContext.name: WebGLRenderContext
lime.graphics.WebGLRenderContext.description:
The WebGLRenderContext allows access to WebGL features when OpenGL, OpenGL ES or
WebGL is the render context type of the Window.

lime.graphics.ImageChannel.name: ImageChannel
lime.graphics.ImageChannel.description: An enum with values for standard image color channels

lime.graphics.ImageFileFormat.name: ImageFileFormat
lime.graphics.ImageFileFormat.description: An enum with values for image encoding formats

lime.graphics.ImageType.name: ImageType
lime.graphics.ImageType.description:
An enum containing values for the underlying image type
represented by an ImageBuffer

lime.graphics.RenderContextAttributes.name: RenderContextAttributes
lime.graphics.RenderContextAttributes.description: Additional options possible for a render context

lime.math.Matrix3.name: Matrix3
lime.math.Matrix3.description:
Matrix3 is a 3x3 transformation matrix particularly useful for
two-dimensional transformation. It can be used for rotation, scale
and skewing of a two-dimensional object.

lime.math.Rectangle.name: Rectangle
lime.math.Rectangle.description:
The Rectangle class provides a simple object for storing
and manipulating a logical rectangle for calculations

lime.math.Vector2.name: Vector2
lime.math.Vector2.description:
The Vector2 class can be used for calculating math with
basic (x, y) coordinates

lime.math.Vector4.name: Vector4
lime.math.Vector4.description:
Vector4 is a vector suitable for three-dimensional
math, containing (x, y, z, w) components

lime.math.ARGB.name: ARGB
lime.math.ARGB.description:
A utility for storing, accessing and converting colors in an ARGB
(alpha, red, green, blue) color format.

lime.math.BGRA.name: BGRA
lime.math.BGRA.description:
A utility for storing, accessing and converting colors in a BGRA
(blue, green, red, alpha) color format.

lime.math.ColorMatrix.name: ColorMatrix
lime.math.ColorMatrix.description:
ColorMatrix is a 4x5 matrix containing color multiplication
and offset values for tinting and other kinds of color
manipulation. In addition to using the multiplier, offset and
color properties, it can be edited directly as a Float32Array

lime.math.RGBA.name: RGBA
lime.math.RGBA.description:
A utility for storing, accessing and converting colors in an RGBA
(red, green, blue, alpha) color format.

lime.utils.Assets.name: Assets
lime.utils.Assets.description:
The Assets class provides a cross-platform interface to access
embedded images, fonts, sounds and other resource files.

nape.callbacks.BodyCallback.name: BodyCallback
nape.callbacks.BodyCallback.description:
Callback object for Body type events.

This, like all other callback objects are automatically reused
and you should not keep any reference to them.

nape.callbacks.BodyListener.name: BodyListener
nape.callbacks.BodyListener.description:
Event listener for Body type events.

The events that can be caught are WAKE and SLEEP type events.
Theses listeners will only operate on Bodys, not Interactors in general.

nape.callbacks.Callback.name: Callback
nape.callbacks.Callback.description:
Base type for Callback event objects.

Callback objects are automatically reused and you should not keep references
to them.

nape.callbacks.CbEvent.name: CbEvent
nape.callbacks.CbEvent.description: Enumeration of possible callback event types.

nape.callbacks.CbType.name: CbType
nape.callbacks.CbType.description:
Callback Type applied to Interactors and Constraints.

Callback types are ranged over by listeners.

nape.callbacks.CbTypeList.name: CbTypeList
nape.callbacks.CbTypeList.description:
Nape list of CbType type objects Internally this list is at present implemented as a linked list with object pooled nodes and iterators with various fast paths made for standard access patterns (For instance accessing successive elements runs in constant time when using random access functions) Iteration of this list can be done in various ways, but the preferred way on all targets, is through use of the foreach function: list.foreach(function (obj) { }); This method is inlined so that in haxe no closure will need to be created. In AS3, a closure would need to be created in general, so for performance reasons you 'may' choose to use iteration as follows: for (var i:int = 0; i < list.length; i++) {

This, like all other callback objects are automatically reused and you should not keep any reference to them.

ConstraintListener

Event listener for Constraint type events.

The events that can be caught are WAKE, SLEEP and BREAK type events. Theses listeners will only operate on Constraints.

OptionType
OptionType representing matching behaviour for Listeners.



An object's set of CbType's 'matches' against an OptionType iff.
the OptionType's includes list intersects the object's set of CbTypes
and the OptionType's excludes list 'does not' intersect the object's set
of CbTypes.

option = new OptionType([A, B], [C, D]);
obj.cbTypes = [] // => does not match option.
obj.cbTypes = [A] // => matches the option
obj.cbTypes = [A, C] // => does not match option.

The optionType's includes and excludes list are managed to be always
disjoint: The action of including an already excluded type serves to
remove it from the excludes list, equalliy excluding an already included
type serves to remove it from the includes list.

var option = new OptionType();
option.including(A); // option = {[A]:[]}
option.excluding(A); // option = {[]:[]}
option.excluding(A); // option = {[]:[A]}
option.including(A); // option = {[A]:[]}

nape.callbacks.PreCallback.name: PreCallback
nape.callbacks.PreCallback.description:
Callback object for Pre-Interaction type events.

This, like all other callback objects are automatically reused
and you should not keep any reference to them.

nape.callbacks.PreFlag.name: PreFlag
nape.callbacks.PreFlag.description:
Enumeration of interaction states for arbiters. These values are returned
by PreListener callback handlers.

nape.callbacks.PreListener.name: PreListener
nape.callbacks.PreListener.description:
Event listener for Pre-Interaction type events.

Pre-Interaction type events can occur between any two Interactors (whether they
be Shapes, Bodys, Compounds or a mix thereof).

nape.constraint.AngleJoint.name: AngleJoint
nape.constraint.AngleJoint.description:
AngleJoint constraining the relative angles of two Bodies.

The equation for this constraint is:

jointMin <= ratio * body2.rotation - body1.rotation <= jointMax

nape.constraint.Constraint.name: Constraint
nape.constraint.Constraint.description: Base type for all Nape joints and constraints

nape.constraint.ConstraintList.name: ConstraintList
nape.constraint.ConstraintList.description:
Nape list of Constraint type objects Internally this list is at present implemented as a linked list with object pooled nodes and iterators with various fast paths made for standard access patterns (For instance accessing successive elements runs in constant time when using random access functions) Iteration of this list can be done in various ways, but the preferred way on all targets, is through use of the foreach function: list.foreach(function (obj) { }); This method is inlined so that in haxe no closure will need to be created. In AS3, a closure would need to be created in general, so for performance reasons you 'may' choose to use iteration as follows: for (var i:int = 0; i < list.length; i++) {

DistanceJoint

DistanceJoint limiting the distance between two local anchor points of Bodies.

The equation for this constraint could be written like: 

jointMin <= distance(body2.localPointToWorld(anchor2), body1.localPointToWorld(anchor1)) <= jointMax

This joint is not designed to work when  jointMin = jointMax = 0  and constraint is
stiff. In this instance you should use a PivotJoint instead.

nape.constraint.LineJoint.name: LineJoint
nape.constraint.LineJoint.description:
LineJoint constraining anchor of one body, to a line segment of the other. The equation for this constraint could be written like:

MotorJoint

MotorJoint constraining the angular velocities of two bodies

The equation for this constraint is: 

(ratio * body2.angularVel) - body1.angularVel = rate

This constraint operates only on the velocities of objects.

nape.constraint.PivotJoint.name: PivotJoint
nape.constraint.PivotJoint.description:
PivotJoint constraining two anchors points of bodies to be equal.

The equation for this constraint is:

body2.localPointToWorld(anchor2) = body1.localPointToWorld(anchor1)

You may view this constraint as being equal to the DistanceJoint constraint
when both its jointMin and jointMax are exactly 0 (In such a case a
DistanceJoint becomes degenerate). Compared to the DistanceJoint this is
a 2 dimensional constraint.

nape.constraint.PulleyJoint.name: PulleyJoint
nape.constraint.PulleyJoint.description:
PulleyJoint limiting the weighted sum of distances between 2 pairs of 4 local anchor points of Bodies.

The equation for this constraint could be written like:

jointMin <= distance(body2.localPointToWorld(anchor2), body1.localPointToWorld(anchor1))
+ ratio * distance(body4.localPointToWorld(anchor4), body3.localPointToWorld(anchor3)) <= jointMax

This joint is not designed to work when either of these pairs achieves a distance of 0, it will still work
but may not be entirely ideal.
!1* * This constraint can be used in a full 4-body set up, or a 3-body set up or a 2-body set up permitting
any arrangement as long as body1 != body2 and body3 != body4

nape.constraint.UserConstraint.name: UserConstraint
nape.constraint.UserConstraint.description:
UserConstraint providing a low-level API for user-defined Constraints.

This API is intended to be powerful enough to model any constraint that
Nape can handle, but not so low level as to be completely prohibitive.

For instance, things like soft-constraints are automatically provided
by this API.

Working with this API will require mathematical skills. A full manual
for this API is provided at: http://napephys.com/help/Constraints.pdf

You may also be interested in the nape-symbolic module that is available
on github/haxelib/nape downloads. Which provides a run-time compiled DSL
using this API to make prototyping (or creating non-performance critical)
user-defined constraints simple without the need for great mathematical
skills as well as being much quicker to work with.

nape.constraint.WeldJoint.name: WeldJoint
nape.constraint.WeldJoint.description:
WeldJoint constraining two bodies to be exactly locked together.

The equation for this constraint is:

[ body2.localPointToWorld(anchor2) ] = [ body1.localPointToWorld(anchor1) ]
[          body2.rotation          ]   [      body1.rotation + phase      ]

This constraint is equivalent to using a PivotJoint and AngleJoint
together except that it is solved as a single constraint and thus
will be more stable.

This constraint is 3 dimensional.

Although this constraint is very stable, if you chain bodies together
using this constraint, you should except to see a small amount of rotation
about the anchor points so you should chose them accordingly.

nape.dynamics.Arbiter.name: Arbiter
nape.dynamics.Arbiter.description:
Arbiter representing the state of an interaction between two Bodys.

These objects are automatically reused, and you should not keep your own
references to them.

nape.geom.AABB.name: AABB
nape.geom.AABB.description:
Axis Aligned Bounding Box (AABB)

Note that in many cases of an AABB object being returned by a Nape function
the AABB object will be marked internally as an 'immutable' AABB. This will
always be documented and trying to mutate such an AABB will result in an
error being thrown.

nape.geom.ConvexResult.name: ConvexResult
nape.geom.ConvexResult.description:
Class representing the results of a convex cast operation.

These objects are allocated from an object pool and can
be released back to that pool by calling its dispose method.

Vec2

2 Dimensional vector.

Note that in many cases of a Vec2 object being returned by a Nape function the Vec2 object will be marked internally as an 'immutable' Vec2. This will always be documented and trying to mutate such a Vec2 will result in an error being thrown.

Vec2 objects can make use of a global object pool, attempting to make use of a disposed Vec2 will also result in an error with the object pool working in a FILO order to increase the likelihood of such misuse being caught.

Additionally Vec2 objects can be created as 'weak'. Passing a weak Vec2 to any Nape function as an argument will result in the automatic disposal of the Vec2 once the method has finished with it. There may be exceptions to this rule which will also be documented; a notable case being the appending of a weak Vec2 to a Nape Vec2List in which case the disposal of the weak Vec2 is performed when that Vec2List is handed to a Nape function instead.

Example: 

var vertices = Polygon.box(20, 20, true);
var polygon = new Polygon(vertices);

In this example, passing true to the Polygon.box method means
that we will be returned a Vec2List containing only 'weak' Vec2s. Upon
passing this Vec2List to the Polygon constructor, all of the Vec2s from
that list will be automatically disposed.

flixel.system.replay.FlxReplay.description:
The replay object both records and replays game recordings,
as well as handle saving and loading replays to and from files.
Gameplay recordings are essentially a list of keyboard and mouse inputs,
but since Flixel is fairly deterministic, we can use these to play back
recordings of gameplay with a decent amount of fidelity.

flixel.system.scaleModes.BaseScaleMode.name: BaseScaleMode
flixel.system.scaleModes.BaseScaleMode.description:
The base class from which all other scale modes extend from.
You can implement your own scale mode by extending this class and overriding the appropriate methods.

flixel.system.scaleModes.FillScaleMode.name: FillScaleMode
flixel.system.scaleModes.FillScaleMode.description:
FillScaleMode is a scaling mode which stretches and squashes the game to exactly fit the provided window.
This may result in the graphics of your game being distorted if the user resizes their game window.

flixel.system.scaleModes.FixedScaleAdjus.name: FixedScaleAdjustSizeScaleMode
flixel.system.scaleModes.FixedScaleAdjus.description:
FixedScaleAdjustSizeScaleMode is a scaling mode which maintains the game's scene at a fixed size.
This will clip off the edges of the scene for dimensions which are too small.
However, unlike FixedScaleMode, this mode will extend the width of the current scene to match the window scale.
The result is that objects that would be offscreen on smaller window sizes will be visible in larger ones.

flixel.system.scaleModes.FixedScaleMode.name: FixedScaleMode
flixel.system.scaleModes.FixedScaleMode.description:
FixedScaleMode is a scaling mode which maintains the game's scene at a fixed size.
This will clip off the edges of the scene for dimensions which are too small,
and leave black margins on the sides for dimensions which are too large.

flixel.system.scaleModes.PixelPerfectSca.name: PixelPerfectScaleMode
flixel.system.scaleModes.PixelPerfectSca.description:
PixelPerfectScaleMode is a scaling mode which maintains the game's aspect ratio.
When you shrink or grow the window, the width and height of the game will adjust,
either scaling the game or adding black bars as needed.

flixel.system.scaleModes.RatioScaleMode.name: RatioScaleMode
flixel.system.scaleModes.RatioScaleMode.description:
RatioScaleMode is a scaling mode which maintains the game's aspect ratio.
When you shrink or grow the window, the width and height of the game will adjust,
either scaling the game or adding black bars as needed.

flixel.system.scaleModes.RelativeScaleMo.name: RelativeScaleMode
flixel.system.scaleModes.RelativeScaleMo.description:
RelativeScaleMode is a scaling mode which stretches and squashes the game to exactly fit the provided window.
It acts similar to the FillScaleMode, however there is one major difference.
RelativeScaleMode takes two parameters, which represent the width scale and height scale.

flixel.system.scaleModes.StageSizeScaleM.name: StageSizeScaleMode
flixel.system.scaleModes.StageSizeScaleM.description:
StageSizeScaleMode is a scaling mode which maintains the game's scene at a fixed size.
This will clip off the edges of the scene for dimensions which are too small.
However, unlike FixedScaleMode, this mode will extend the width of the current scene to match the window scale.
The result is that objects that would be offscreen on smaller window sizes will be visible in larger ones.
